# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gitops-workflows
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gitops-workflows/application-lifecycle-management] ALM is a broader perspective than the Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC), which is limited to the phases of software development such as requirements, design, coding, testing, configuration, project management, and change management.
[src:gitops-workflows/application-lifecycle-management] ALM continues after development until the application is no longer used, and may span many SDLCs.
[src:gitops-workflows/application-lifecycle-management] A research director with research firm Gartner proposed changing the term ALM to ADLM (Application Development Life-cycle Management) to include DevOps, the software engineering culture and practice that aims at unifying software development (Dev) and software operation (Ops).
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:gitops-workflows/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] In network routing, the **control plane** is the part of the router architecture that is concerned with establishing the network topology, or the information in a routing table that defines what to do with incoming packets.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Control plane functions, such as participating in routing protocols, run in the architectural control element.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] In most cases, the routing table contains a list of destination addresses and the outgoing interface or interfaces associated with each.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Control plane logic can also identify certain packets to be discarded, as well as preferential treatment of certain packets for which a high quality of service is defined by such mechanisms as differentiated services.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Depending on the specific router implementation, there may be a separate forwarding information base that is populated by the control plane, but used by the high-speed forwarding plane to look up packets and decide how to handle them.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] In computing, the control plane is the part of the software that configures and shuts down the data plane.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] By contrast, the data plane is the part of the software that processes the data requests.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The data plane is also sometimes referred to as the forwarding plane.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The distinction has proven useful in the networking field where it originated, as it separates the concerns: the data plane is optimized for speed of processing, and for simplicity and regularity.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The control plane is optimized for customizability, handling policies, handling exceptional situations, and in general facilitating and simplifying the data plane processing.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] A major function of the control plane is deciding which routes go into the main routing table.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] "Main" refers to the table that holds the unicast routes that are active.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Multicast routing may require an additional routing table for multicast routes.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Several routing protocols e.g., IS-IS, OSPF and BGP maintain internal databases of candidate routes which are promoted when a route fails or when a routing policy is changed.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Several different information sources may provide information about a route to a given destination, but the router must select the "best" route to install into the routing table.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] In some cases, there may be multiple routes of equal "quality", and the router may install all of them and load-share across them.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Routers forward traffic that enters on an input interface and leaves on an output interface, subject to filtering and other local rules.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] While routers usually forward from one physical (e.g., Ethernet, serial) to another physical interface, it is also possible to define multiple logical interfaces on a physical interface.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] A physical Ethernet interface, for example, can have logical interfaces in several virtual LANs defined by IEEE 802.1Q VLAN headers.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] When an interface has an address configured in a subnet, such as 192.0.2.1 in the 192.0.2.0/24 (i.e., subnet mask 255.255.255.0) subnet, and that interface is considered "up" by the router, the router thus has a directly connected route to 192.0.2.0/24.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If a routing protocol offered another router's route to that same subnet, the routing table installation software will normally ignore the dynamic route and prefer the directly connected route.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] There also may be software-only interfaces on the router, which it treats as if they were locally connected.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] For example, most implementations have a "null" software-defined interface.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Packets having this interface as a next hop will be discarded, which can be a very efficient way to filter traffic.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Routers usually can route traffic faster than they can examine it and compare it to filters, so, if the criterion for discarding is the packet's destination address, "blackholing" the traffic will be more efficient than explicit filters.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Other software-defined interfaces that are treated as directly connected, as long as they are active, are interfaces associated with tunneling protocols such as Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE) or Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS).
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Loopback interfaces are virtual interfaces that are considered directly connected interfaces.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Router configuration rules may contain static routes.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] A static route minimally has a destination address, a prefix length or subnet mask, and a definition of where to send packets for the route.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] That definition can refer to a local interface on the router, or a next-hop address that could be on the far end of a subnet to which the router is connected.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The next-hop address could also be on a subnet that is directly connected, and, before the router can determine if the static route is usable, it must do a **recursive lookup** of the next hop address in the local routing table.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If the next-hop address is reachable, the static route is usable, but if the next-hop is unreachable, the route is ignored.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Static routes also may have preference factors used to select the best static route to the same destination.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] One application is called a **floating static route**, where the static route is less preferred than a route from any routing protocol.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The static route, which might use a dial-up link or other slow medium, activates only when the dynamic routing protocol(s) cannot provide a route to the destination.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Static routes that are more preferred than any dynamic route can also be very useful, especially when using traffic engineering principles to make certain traffic go over a specific path with an engineered quality of service.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The routing table manager, according to implementation and configuration rules, may select a particular route or routes from those advertised by various routing protocols.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Different implementations have different sets of preferences for routing information, and these are not standardized among IP routers.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] It is fair to say that subnets on directly connected active interfaces are always preferred.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Beyond that, however, there will be differences.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Implementers generally have a numerical preference, which Cisco calls an "administrative distance", for route selection.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] The lower the preference, the more desirable the route.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Cisco's IOS implementation makes exterior BGP the most preferred source of dynamic routing information, while Nortel RS makes intra-area OSPF most preferred.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If the route is "more specific" than an existing route, install it in addition to the existing routes.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] "More specific" means that it has a longer prefix.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If the route is of equal specificity to a route already in the routing table, but comes from a more preferred source of routing information, replace the route in the table.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If the routes are of equal metric and the router supports load-sharing, add the new route and designate it as part of a load-sharing group.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Typically, implementations will support a maximum number of routes that load-share to the same destination.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If that maximum is already in the table, the new route is usually dropped.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] See forwarding plane for more detail, but each implementation has its own means of updating the forwarding information base (FIB) with new routes installed in the routing table.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If the FIB is in one-to-one correspondence with the RIB, the new route is installed in the FIB after it is in the RIB.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] If the FIB is smaller than the RIB, and the FIB uses a hash table or other data structure that does not easily update, the existing FIB might be invalidated and replaced with a new one computed from the updated RIB.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Multicast routing builds on unicast routing.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] Each multicast group to which the local router can route has a multicast routing table entry with a next hop for the group, rather than for a specific destination as in unicast routing.
[src:gitops-workflows/control-plane] There can be multicast static routes as well as learning dynamic multicast routes from a protocol such as Protocol Independent Multicast (PIM).
[src:gitops-workflows/core-concepts] Let's assume you're familiar with core Git, Docker, Kubernetes, Continuous Delivery, and GitOps concepts.
[src:gitops-workflows/core-concepts] Below are some of the concepts that are specific to Argo CD.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:gitops-workflows/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] In the Gitless GitOps model, the Flux controllers are fully decoupled from Git, relying solely on container registries as the source of truth for the desired state of Kubernetes clusters.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] From a user perspective, Git remains the primary interface for managing the desired state, but the underlying implementation leverages OCI-compliant registries to store and distribute the configuration artifacts.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] This approach allows for greater flexibility and scalability, the Git server is no longer a production dependency, while the OCI registry becomes the unified source of truth for all configuration artifacts, SBOMs, cryptographic signatures, and app images.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] In Flux, *GitOps Toolkit* refers to a collection of specialized tools, Flux Controllers, composable APIs, and reusable Go packages available under the fluxcd GitHub organization.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] These components are designed for the purpose of constructing Continuous Delivery workflows on Kubernetes using GitOps principles.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The GitOps Toolkit serves as the foundation for managing and automating the deployment and configuration of applications and infrastructure within a Kubernetes cluster, promoting a declarative and version-controlled approach to operations.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at GitOps Toolkit components.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The `Kustomization` custom resource represents a local set of Kubernetes resources (e.g. kustomize overlay) that Flux is supposed to reconcile in the cluster.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The reconciliation runs every five minutes by default, but this can be changed with `.spec.interval`.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] If you make any changes to the cluster using `kubectl edit/patch/delete`, they will be promptly reverted.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] You either suspend the reconciliation or push your changes to a Git repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at the Kustomize FAQ and the Kustomization CRD.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The process of installing the Flux components in a GitOps manner is called a *bootstrap*.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The manifests are applied to the cluster, a `GitRepository` and `Kustomization` are created for the Flux components, then the manifests are pushed to an existing Git repository (or a new one is created).
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] Flux can manage itself just as it manages other resources.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The bootstrap is done using the `flux` CLI or using our Terraform Provider.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at the bootstrap documentation.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at continuous delivery as defined in the CNCF.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at continuous delivery as defined in the CNCF Glossary.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] Developers can use techniques like feature flags, canary releases, and A/B testing to minimize the chances of introducing bugs or errors that could harm users or interrupt business operations.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] These strategies enable a controlled and gradual rollout of new features, ensuring a smooth and successful release that enhances user trust and improves the overall user experience.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] The Flux project offers a specialised controller called Flagger that implements various progressive delivery techniques.
[src:gitops-workflows/flux-concepts] For more information, take a look at Flagger deployment strategies.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:gitops-workflows/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:gitops-workflows/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
